    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-10-24T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-10-24T07:00:00-05:00" n="100"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d100">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">780.5/10–2452: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 100<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Iraq (<persName corresp="#p_BBY1"
                            type="from">Berry</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d100fn1">Repeated to Amman, London, Ankara, Paris, Beirut,
                        Damascus, Cairo, and Jidda.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Baghdad</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-10-24T15:00:00+03:00"
                            >October 24, 1952—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>531. Re London’s 2304 Oct 20.<note n="2" xml:id="d100fn2">
                        <ref target="#d97">Document 97</ref>.</note> Emb doubts that Iraq can or
                    shld be split off from other Arab states in regard participation in <gloss
                        target="#t_MEDO1">MEDO</gloss> or that Turks can be useful broach this subj
                    to Iraq Govt. It is probably true that Regent,<note n="3" xml:id="d100fn3">Crown
                        Prince <persName corresp="#p_IAA1">Abdul Ilah</persName>, uncle of King
                            <persName corresp="#p_FF1">Faisal II</persName> who was a minor.</note>
                    with his personal pro-Western inclinations, displayed favorable attitude in
                    discussing <gloss target="#t_MEDO1">MEDO</gloss> with Turk <gloss
                        target="#t_PriMin1">PriMin</gloss> in London, but bringing Iraq Govt as
                    whole to make break with other Arab states not only difficult but probably also
                    inadvisable from standpoint Iraqs internal stability. In any case present
                    caretaker Iraq Govt in no position to make decision.</p>
                <p>If <gloss target="#t_MEDO1">MEDO</gloss> made sufficiently attractive Iraqis cld
                    be persuaded use their influence in discussion with other Arab states to bring
                    about collective Arab decision participate in <gloss target="#t_MEDO1"
                        >MEDO</gloss> but in this Emb’s view Egypt must also be persuaded before
                    positive Arab action likely.</p>
                <p>Anti-Turk sentiment presently so high here that Emb doubts if Turk intervention
                    wld be fruitful. Turk has no Amb here and intervention by Chargé ahead of Brit
                    and US Amb might not only create suspicion concerning Turk motive but also give
                    impression that US and UK were trying to get out-from-under.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BBY1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berry</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
